---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Actors | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Actors working internationally, covering film and television careers abroad, theater positions, and global entertainment opportunities.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Actors";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Actors working abroad, performing internationally, and pursuing careers across film, television, and theater productions worldwide.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/actor-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/actor-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Acting Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Actors bring characters to life across film, television, and theater. International acting careers offer opportunities to work on global productions, perform in international theater companies, and build careers across entertainment industries worldwide.
      </p>
      <p>
        International acting opportunities exist through international film and television productions, touring theater companies, work permits for major productions abroad, and the global nature of modern entertainment production.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Actors working abroad across film, television, and theater productions worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Actors</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'General health coverage', why: 'Professional health maintenance', typical: 'Often self-arranged' },
          { need: 'Physical injury coverage', why: 'Performance and stunt demands', typical: 'Important for role' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Career and performance pressure', typical: 'Consider including' },
          { need: 'Voice coverage', why: 'Professional tool', typical: 'Consider for profession' },
          { need: 'Appearance maintenance', why: 'Professional requirement', typical: 'Consider inclusion' },
          { need: 'Income gaps coverage', why: 'Employment variability', typical: 'Plan for gaps' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Physical Performance</h3>
      <p>
        Acting often involves physical demands—stunts, action sequences, physically demanding roles. Even without stunt work, long hours on set, costume requirements, and performance demands create physical stress. Coverage for performance-related injuries is important.
      </p>
      <p>
        Productions typically provide production insurance, but this may not cover everything. Understanding the interplay between production coverage and personal coverage helps ensure adequate protection.
      </p>

      <h3>Mental Health</h3>
      <p>
        Acting careers involve intense psychological demands—rejection, performance anxiety, emotional roles, and career uncertainty. Mental health support is particularly valuable for sustaining acting careers over time.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Film Production</h3>
      <p>
        Feature film work. Production coverage while working. Project-based. Film offers scale.
      </p>

      <h3>Television</h3>
      <p>
        Series and episodic work. Production coverage during series. More consistent schedule. TV offers continuity.
      </p>

      <h3>Theater</h3>
      <p>
        Stage performance. Theater company benefits possible. Live performance. Theater offers craft.
      </p>

      <h3>Commercial</h3>
      <p>
        Advertising and commercial work. Production coverage brief. Short-term projects. Commercial offers income.
      </p>

      <h3>Voice Acting</h3>
      <p>
        Animation and voice work. Studio environment. Less physical. Voice offers flexibility.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Actors"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Actors working abroad across film, television, and theater productions worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Acting Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>Training</h3>
      <p>
        Drama school, conservatory, degree. Technique development. Foundation training. Education provides base.
      </p>

      <h3>Credits</h3>
      <p>
        Film, TV, theater credits. Resume building. Role progression. Credits demonstrate experience.
      </p>

      <h3>Union Membership</h3>
      <p>
        SAG-AFTRA, Equity, BECTU, etc. Professional standing. Benefits access. Union provides protection.
      </p>

      <h3>Representation</h3>
      <p>
        Agent and manager. Career guidance. Opportunity access. Representation enables career.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Physical Demands</h3>
      <p>
        Performance requirements. Stunt work. Long hours. Physical coverage important.
      </p>

      <h3>Voice</h3>
      <p>
        Professional voice use. Projection demands. Vocal strain possible. Voice coverage consideration.
      </p>

      <h3>Mental Health</h3>
      <p>
        Rejection common. Performance anxiety. Role immersion. Mental health support valuable.
      </p>

      <h3>Appearance</h3>
      <p>
        Physical appearance professional requirement. Maintenance demands. Dental and skin health. Appearance coverage consideration.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Performance</h3>
      <p>
        Character embodiment. Scene work. Emotional availability. Performance is the work.
      </p>

      <h3>Preparation</h3>
      <p>
        Script study. Character development. Physical preparation. Preparation enables performance.
      </p>

      <h3>Auditions</h3>
      <p>
        Constant audition cycle. Self-tape demands. Rejection processing. Auditions secure work.
      </p>

      <h3>Business</h3>
      <p>
        Career management. Self-promotion. Relationship building. Business sustains career.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Global Industry</h3>
      <p>
        Entertainment production global. International co-productions common. Streaming expanding markets. Opportunities worldwide.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        Background to lead. Character actor. Star. Producer-actor. Multiple paths.
      </p>

      <h3>Income Variability</h3>
      <p>
        Work sporadic for most. Major gaps common. Financial planning essential. Variability is norm.
      </p>

      <h3>Competition</h3>
      <p>
        Extremely competitive field. Many seeking few roles. Persistence required. Competition intense.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm an actor considering international work. What should I know?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Self-arranged coverage typically needed between jobs. Mental health support valuable. Work permits required. Union status affects options.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Do productions provide coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Productions typically have insurance during filming. Doesn't cover gaps. Personal coverage needed for continuity. Verify specific production provisions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What about union health coverage internationally?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            US unions may provide domestic coverage. International work varies. Research specific union provisions. Often need supplemental coverage abroad.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Is mental health coverage important for actors?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Yes for career sustainability. Rejection demanding. Performance pressure real. Mental health support valuable.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">How do I handle coverage during employment gaps?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Plan for gaps in coverage. Continuous personal coverage recommended. Budget for premiums during unemployment. Gaps are normal.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What's the career outlook?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Streaming expanding production. Competition intense. International productions increasing. Outlook varies significantly by individual.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by ensuring continuous coverage that bridges employment gaps. Consider mental health support for career demands. Understand production coverage versus personal coverage. Build international relationships through audition and networking.
      </p>
      <p>
        Actors bring stories to life worldwide. Your coverage should support performance careers—addressing physical demands, supporting mental health, and maintaining coverage across acting work worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Acting Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Actors working abroad across film, television, and theater productions worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
